            "abstractNote": "Maximumurine concentratingability was determined for 11 species of insectivorous bats by water-deprivationexperiments. Mean maximumconcentrations ranged from 2,640 to 4,340 milliosmols/kg water. Renal indices involved with medullary thickness were highly correlated with urine concentrating ability (for example, r = .919 for the ratio of inner medullary zone:cortex, IM/C). Mean maximum urine concentrating abilities for six additional species were predicted from the following equation: mean maximum osmolality (mosmol/kg) = 658 + 558 (IM/C). The insectivorous bats limited to more arid habitats possessed better renal adaptationsfor water conservation.Under naturalconditions arid-adaptedspecies drinkwhen water is available; however, indirect evidence suggests that some may be able to survive long periods without water.",
